        slug="kotor-remake-saber-confirmed-still-in-development"
        url={SLUG}
      >

        <p className="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
          <strong>REDMOND, WA</strong> — Five years after its spine-tingling cinematic reveal
          at a PlayStation Showcase, the remake of{' '}
          <strong>Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic</strong> is still in development.
          That confirmation came from <strong>Saber Interactive</strong> Chief Creative Officer{' '}
          <strong>Tim Willits</strong> in an interview with IGN on March 6, 2026, in the
          form of exactly 11 words:
        </p>

        <blockquote className="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-5 py-2 my-6 bg-blue-50 rounded-r-lg">
          <p className="italic text-gray-800 text-xl leading-relaxed">
            &ldquo;Yes, it is still in development. That&apos;s all I can say.&rdquo;
          </p>
          <footer className="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2">
            — Tim Willits, Chief Creative Officer, Saber Interactive
          </footer>
        </blockquote>

        <p className="leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The terse statement marks the first direct on-record confirmation of the
          project&apos;s status since a December 2025 report shed new light on the
          remake&apos;s turbulent behind-the-scenes history. It also, bittersweet as it
          is, prevents another wave of cancellation rumors that the{' '}
          <Link href="/video-games" className="text-blue-600 hover:underline">
            Star Wars gaming community
          </Link>{' '}
          has endured with increasing regularity since 2022.
        </p>

        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">
          A Troubled Legacy: From Aspyr to Saber — and Now Mad Head Games
        </h2>

        <p className="leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The KOTOR remake was originally announced on September 9, 2021, at a PlayStation
          Showcase — a cinematic teaser with no gameplay, no engine footage, and a{' '}
          <strong>&ldquo;In Development&rdquo;</strong> label rather than a release
          window. The initial buzz was enormous; KOTOR (2003) is widely considered one of
          the greatest RPGs of all time, and fans had waited nearly two decades for a
          modern reimagining.
        </p>

        <p className="leading-relaxed mb-6">
          What followed was a development story that has become one of gaming&apos;s
          most closely watched — and most disheartening — sagas:
        </p>

        <ul className="mb-6 space-y-5">
          <li className="flex gap-3">
            <span className="text-blue-500 font-bold text-lg mt-0.5 shrink-0">■</span>
            <div>
              <strong>The Aspyr Pause (2022).</strong> The project was originally helmed by
              Austin-based studio <strong>Aspyr Media</strong>, known for its high-fidelity
              ports of classic Star Wars titles. In mid-2022, Bloomberg and other outlets
              reported the project had been &ldquo;paused indefinitely&rdquo; after Aspyr
              showed a preview build to Lucasfilm and Sony that was deemed insufficient.
              Key leads on the project were let go. No official statement was issued.
            </div>
          </li>
          <li className="flex gap-3">
            <span className="text-blue-500 font-bold text-lg mt-0.5 shrink-0">■</span>
            <div>
              <strong>The Saber Handoff.</strong> Development responsibility was transferred
              to <strong>Saber Interactive</strong> — the studio behind the{' '}
              <em>World War Z</em> game and most recently <em>Space Marine 2</em>. Saber
              officially confirmed their involvement in 2023 but offered no timeline,
              no screenshots, and no engine details. The studio has said only that it
              is &ldquo;rebuilding&rdquo; the project from earlier work.
            </div>
          </li>
          <li className="flex gap-3">
            <span className="text-blue-500 font-bold text-lg mt-0.5 shrink-0">■</span>
            <div>
              <strong>Mad Head Games Co-Development (2025–2026).</strong> Reports from
              late 2025 — corroborated by multiple sources familiar with the project — indicate
              that <strong>Mad Head Games</strong>, the Serbian studio currently working on{' '}
              <em>Hellraiser: Revival</em>, has joined as a co-developer on the remake.
              The exact division of responsibilities between Saber and Mad Head is not
              publicly known.
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">Sony&apos;s Retreat</h2>

        <p className="leading-relaxed mb-6">
          One of the most visible signs of the project&apos;s uncertain trajectory is{' '}
          <strong>Sony Interactive Entertainment&apos;s</strong> progressive withdrawal from
          public association with the title. Sony originally marketed the KOTOR remake as a{' '}
          <strong>PS5 console launch exclusive</strong> — a flagship title meant to demonstrate
          the platform&apos;s power and Sony&apos;s relationship with the Star Wars franchise.
          That positioning has quietly evaporated. The title has been scrubbed from Sony&apos;s
          official PS5 landing pages, blog posts promoting the showcase, and first-party
          marketing materials. Sony has not confirmed whether the exclusivity arrangement
          remains in force.
        </p>

        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">
          The &ldquo;Juliet&rdquo; Codename: A KOTOR II Remake That May Never Be
        </h2>

        <p className="leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Perhaps the most striking detail to emerge from late 2025 reporting was the
          existence of a project internally codenamed <strong>&ldquo;Juliet&rdquo;</strong> —
          a full remake of <em>KOTOR II: The Sith Lords</em> (Obsidian Entertainment, 2004)
          that was at one point on the roadmap alongside the first remake. Sources described
          &ldquo;Juliet&rdquo; as contingent on the commercial and critical success of the
          first game, and those plans are now reportedly <strong>shelved indefinitely</strong>{' '}
          until — and only if — the original remake actually ships.
        </p>

        <p className="leading-relaxed mb-6">
          For fans of <em>The Sith Lords</em> — widely considered the superior game by a
          vocal subset of KOTOR devotees — that news adds an additional layer of stakes
          to a project that already feels like it is balancing on a knife&apos;s edge.
        </p>

        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">Five Years of Waiting: The Numbers</h2>

        <div className="overflow-x-auto mb-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 shadow-sm">
          <table className="w-full text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr className="bg-gray-900 text-white">
                <th className="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold">Date</th>
                <th className="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold">Event</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody className="divide-y divide-gray-100">
              <tr className="hover:bg-gray-50">
                <td className="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-900">Sept 9, 2021</td>
                <td className="px-4 py-3 text-gray-700">PlayStation Showcase reveal — cinematic teaser, no gameplay, no date. Developer: Aspyr Media.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr className="hover:bg-gray-50">
                <td className="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-900">Mid-2022</td>
                <td className="px-4 py-3 text-gray-700">Project "paused indefinitely." Aspyr leads reportedly let go after preview build fails to impress Lucasfilm/Sony.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr className="hover:bg-gray-50">
                <td className="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-900">2023</td>
                <td className="px-4 py-3 text-gray-700">Saber Interactive confirmed as new lead developer. No timeline, screenshots, or engine details provided.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr className="hover:bg-gray-50">
                <td className="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-900">Late 2025</td>
                <td className="px-4 py-3 text-gray-700">Reports surface: Mad Head Games co-developing. "Juliet" (KOTOR II remake) codename revealed and shelved.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr className="hover:bg-gray-50">
                <td className="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-900">March 6, 2026</td>
                <td className="px-4 py-3 text-gray-700">Tim Willits (Saber CCO) confirms to IGN: "Yes, it is still in development. That's all I can say."</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">What Fans Are Saying</h2>

        <p className="leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Reaction across Reddit, the official Star Wars fan communities, and{' '}
          <Link href="/video-games/news" className="text-blue-600 hover:underline">
            gaming forums
          </Link>{' '}
          ranges from cautious relief to exasperated disbelief. The confirmation does forestall
          the most feared outcome — an official cancellation announcement — but many fans note
          that &ldquo;still in development&rdquo; after five years with zero gameplay shown
          is a phrase that offers cold comfort.
        </p>

        <blockquote className="border-l-4 border-gray-400 pl-5 py-2 my-6 bg-gray-50 rounded-r-lg">
          <p className="italic text-gray-800 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            &ldquo;At this point, &lsquo;still in development&rsquo; is doing the same
            work as &lsquo;we haven&rsquo;t given up.&rsquo; It&rsquo;s the digital
            equivalent of a light still being on.&rdquo;
          </p>
          <footer className="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2">
            — Community reaction, r/kotor
          </footer>
        </blockquote>

        <p className="leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The community remembers that <em>Duke Nukem Forever</em> was also &ldquo;in
          development&rdquo; for 14 years before its 2011 release — and that game
          arrived to significant critical disappointment. The pressure on Saber to
          deliver something that honors the original is immense by any measure.
        </p>

        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">The Bigger Picture</h2>

        <p className="leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The KOTOR remake sits inside a broader moment of accountability for the{' '}
          <Link href="/video-games" className="text-blue-600 hover:underline">
            AAA gaming industry
          </Link>{' '}
          around announcement practices. The trend of revealing games years — sometimes a
          decade — before they ship has drawn sustained criticism from players, developers,
          and analysts who argue that early reveals build unsustainable hype and damage
          trust when development realities intervene. Saber&apos;s 11-word statement is,
          in its own way, a product of that culture: a studio that genuinely cannot say
          more than it can say.
        </p>

        <p className="leading-relaxed mb-6">
          For now, the light is still on. Whether the remake that eventually emerges
          will live up to one of the most beloved RPGs in gaming history — or whether
          &ldquo;still in development&rdquo; eventually becomes the epitaph of a
          decade-long development saga — remains entirely to be seen.
        </p>

        <hr className="my-8 border-gray-200" />

        <p className="text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed">
          Related ObjectWire coverage:{' '}
          <Link href="/video-games" className="text-blue-600 hover:underline">Video Games Hub</Link>
